4. Why now

Three market shifts make this feasible now:

First, major ecosystem players are standardizing for agentic commerce. Google’s UCP is designed as an open standard for direct buying from AI surfaces, and Shopify says it co-developed UCP so agents can connect and transact with merchants more easily.  

Second, payments networks are explicitly preparing for delegated transactions. Visa’s Intelligent Commerce, Mastercard Agent Pay, and PayPal’s agentic commerce tooling all point toward AI-assisted or AI-executed purchases becoming a mainstream infrastructure category rather than a fringe experiment.  

Third, the retailer access layer is uneven, which creates an opening for a convenience OS. Instacart, DoorDash, Uber Direct, and Walgreens all expose meaningful APIs or partner programs; Walmart’s public APIs are real but oriented around marketplace and fulfillment workflows; Amazon’s public programmable surfaces are narrower and more controlled, like Buy with Prime and SP-API policies.  

At the same time, we should assume platform friction is real. Amazon’s litigation against Perplexity over agentic shopping on Amazon is a live reminder that some retailers may view third-party shopping agents as adversarial once they start disintermediating the front door.  

