13. Retailer and platform strategy

We should optimize first for selection + speed + access, not retailer prestige.

13.1 Best starting access layers

Instacart is a top early platform because it explicitly offers APIs to build custom shopping experiences across its retailer network and connect users to products from local stores.  

DoorDash and Uber Direct are strong for local delivery orchestration and speed-sensitive use cases, with public developer tooling and APIs for delivery workflows.  

Walgreens is interesting for pharmacy/convenience because it has a formal developer program and API access.  

13.2 Strategic but harder platforms

Walmart matters for value and national breadth, but its official public APIs are oriented around marketplace partners, sellers, and fulfillment workflows rather than a consumer super-agent experience.  

Amazon matters enormously for customer expectations on selection and speed, but public programmable access is more limited and controlled; Buy with Prime is a merchant-side surface, and Amazon’s broader developer ecosystem is policy-governed and revocable.  

Target is strategically relevant, but the publicly visible movement appears more aligned with conversational discovery and advertising than open delegated checkout. Target is currently testing contextual ads in ChatGPT through Roundel.  

13.3 MVP retailer thesis

For v1, the product should say:
“We use the stores you already trust, optimized for price, speed, and fit.”

Practical v1 stack:
	•	Instacart for local grocery breadth
	•	DoorDash / Uber Direct for local speed and delivery orchestration
	•	Walgreens for pharmacy/convenience cases
	•	Walmart where partnership/access is practical
	•	Amazon as roadmap-critical, not MVP-critical

