15. Policy engine

This is a first-class product surface.

Policy objects
	•	max spend by order
	•	max spend by category
	•	monthly limits
	•	preferred merchants
	•	banned merchants
	•	preferred brands
	•	banned brands
	•	shipping urgency rules
	•	substitution rules
	•	approval requirements
	•	allowed payment methods
	•	auto-buy-allowed categories
	•	merchant trust thresholds
	•	third-party seller rules
	•	return-window minimums

Example rules
	•	never buy electronics over $500 without asking
	•	for pantry staples, optimize lowest delivered total
	•	never buy from third-party sellers with weak returns
	•	only use same-day delivery for urgent categories
	•	do not auto-buy apparel
	•	only use Walgreens for OTC and convenience, not general household
	•	never use BNPL

16. Confidence engine

The confidence engine determines whether the system should:
	•	recommend
	•	ask
	•	buy
	•	wait

Inputs
	•	preference match score
	•	recurrence score
	•	category risk score
	•	merchant reliability
	•	price deviation from norm
	•	substitute similarity
	•	reversibility of transaction
	•	shipping fit
	•	household context fit
	•	user trust tier in category

Output bands
	•	0–39: recommend only
	•	40–64: ask questions
	•	65–84: propose purchase
	•	85–94: buy with stop window
	•	95+: proactive auto-buy if policy permits

17. Payments and execution

AiPay should evolve into the delegated transaction layer.

Responsibilities
	•	tokenized payment credentials
	•	delegated authority scope
	•	order approval state machine
	•	merchant execution connectors
	•	receipts and audit trail
	•	exception handling
	•	identity and shipping preferences

Design principle

The user is always the principal.
The agent acts as an authorized delegate within explicit policy.

18. Post-purchase control and recovery

A core trust feature.

Transaction states
	•	Pending: not yet submitted
	•	Cancelable: can stop before merchant processes
	•	Reversible: merchant return/exchange still available
	•	Irreversible: cannot unwind or extremely costly

User controls
	•	cancel
	•	swap item
	•	change retailer
	•	adjust delivery speed
	•	review rationale
	•	report bad choice
	•	tighten autonomy

Product requirement

Every autonomous action must include:
	•	what happened
	•	why it happened
	•	what can still be changed
	•	how to reduce future repeats of the same mistake

